</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Multidetector coronary computed tomography (CT), which is widely performed to assess coronary artery disease noninvasively and accurately, provides excellent image quality. Use of electrocardiography (ECG)–controlled tube current modulation and low tube voltage can reduce patient exposure to nephrotoxic contrast media and carcinogenic radiation when using standard coronary CT with a retrospective ECG-gated helical scan. Various imaging techniques are expected to overcome the limitations of standard coronary CT, which also include insufficient spatial and temporal resolution, beam-hardening artifacts, limited coronary plaque characterization, and an inability to allow functional assessment of coronary stenosis. Use of a step-and-shoot scan, iterative reconstruction, and a high-pitch dual-source helical scan can further reduce radiation dose. Dual-energy CT can improve contrast medium enhancement and reasonably reduce the contrast dose when combined with noise reduction with the use of iterative reconstruction. High-definition CT can improve spatial resolution and diagnostic evaluation of small or peripheral coronary vessels and coronary stents. Dual-source CT and a motion correction algorithm can improve temporal resolution and reduce coronary motion artifacts. Whole-heart coverage with 320-detector CT and an intelligent boundary registration algorithm can eliminate stair-step artifacts. By decreasing beam hardening and enabling material decomposition, dual-energy CT is expected to remove or reduce the depiction of coronary calcification to improve intraluminal evaluation of calcified vessels and to provide detailed analysis of coronary plaque components and accurate qualitative and quantitative assessment of myocardial perfusion. Fractional flow reserve derived from coronary CT is a state-of-the-art noninvasive technique for accurately identifying myocardial ischemia beyond coronary CT. Understanding these techniques is important to enhance the value of coronary CT for assessment of coronary artery disease.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140181">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140181">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig1a.jpeg" height="243" width="1679" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Schematic diagrams show the different relationships between radiation dose and the cardiac cycle with various scanning techniques for coronary CT. The height of the shaded box represents the amount of tube current. <b>(a)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan, radiation is delivered with a constant tube current throughout the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation, the tube current is extremely reduced outside the predetermined cardiac phases. <b>(c)</b> For a prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated axial scan (step-and-shoot scan), radiation is delivered only during the predetermined cardiac phases. After an axial scan covering a wide area is performed during selected phases at a certain table location, the table is moved to the next location, with little overlapping with the following axial scan. <b>(d)</b> A prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated high-pitch dual-source helical scan enables complete coverage of the heart within the selected phases of a single cardiac cycle and is associated with the lowest radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig1b.jpeg" height="243" width="1670" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Schematic diagrams show the different relationships between radiation dose and the cardiac cycle with various scanning techniques for coronary CT. The height of the shaded box represents the amount of tube current. <b>(a)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan, radiation is delivered with a constant tube current throughout the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation, the tube current is extremely reduced outside the predetermined cardiac phases. <b>(c)</b> For a prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated axial scan (step-and-shoot scan), radiation is delivered only during the predetermined cardiac phases. After an axial scan covering a wide area is performed during selected phases at a certain table location, the table is moved to the next location, with little overlapping with the following axial scan. <b>(d)</b> A prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated high-pitch dual-source helical scan enables complete coverage of the heart within the selected phases of a single cardiac cycle and is associated with the lowest radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig1c.jpeg" height="451" width="1672" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Schematic diagrams show the different relationships between radiation dose and the cardiac cycle with various scanning techniques for coronary CT. The height of the shaded box represents the amount of tube current. <b>(a)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan, radiation is delivered with a constant tube current throughout the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation, the tube current is extremely reduced outside the predetermined cardiac phases. <b>(c)</b> For a prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated axial scan (step-and-shoot scan), radiation is delivered only during the predetermined cardiac phases. After an axial scan covering a wide area is performed during selected phases at a certain table location, the table is moved to the next location, with little overlapping with the following axial scan. <b>(d)</b> A prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated high-pitch dual-source helical scan enables complete coverage of the heart within the selected phases of a single cardiac cycle and is associated with the lowest radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig1d.jpeg" height="290" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Schematic diagrams show the different relationships between radiation dose and the cardiac cycle with various scanning techniques for coronary CT. The height of the shaded box represents the amount of tube current. <b>(a)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan, radiation is delivered with a constant tube current throughout the cardiac cycle. <b>(b)</b> For a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation, the tube current is extremely reduced outside the predetermined cardiac phases. <b>(c)</b> For a prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated axial scan (step-and-shoot scan), radiation is delivered only during the predetermined cardiac phases. After an axial scan covering a wide area is performed during selected phases at a certain table location, the table is moved to the next location, with little overlapping with the following axial scan. <b>(d)</b> A prospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated high-pitch dual-source helical scan enables complete coverage of the heart within the selected phases of a single cardiac cycle and is associated with the lowest radiation dose.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig2a.jpeg" height="992" width="699" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 1.17 mSv) performed with a step-and-shoot scan with 100-kVp tube voltage provides high spatial resolution and adequate image noise in combination with high-definition CT and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction (50% blending ratio with filtered backprojection) on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig2b.jpeg" height="828" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 1.17 mSv) performed with a step-and-shoot scan with 100-kVp tube voltage provides high spatial resolution and adequate image noise in combination with high-definition CT and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction (50% blending ratio with filtered backprojection) on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig2c.jpeg" height="828" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 1.17 mSv) performed with a step-and-shoot scan with 100-kVp tube voltage provides high spatial resolution and adequate image noise in combination with high-definition CT and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction (50% blending ratio with filtered backprojection) on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig3a.jpeg" height="857" width="813" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 0.97 mSv) performed with a high-pitch dual-source helical scan with 100-kVp tube voltage offers excellent image quality on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>. (Images courtesy of Nobuo Iguchi, MD, PhD, Department of Cardiology, Sakakibara Heart Institute, Tokyo, Japan.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig3b.jpeg" height="857" width="415" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 0.97 mSv) performed with a high-pitch dual-source helical scan with 100-kVp tube voltage offers excellent image quality on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>. (Images courtesy of Nobuo Iguchi, MD, PhD, Department of Cardiology, Sakakibara Heart Institute, Tokyo, Japan.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig3c.jpeg" height="857" width="423" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Low-dose coronary CT (effective dose, 0.97 mSv) performed with a high-pitch dual-source helical scan with 100-kVp tube voltage offers excellent image quality on a volume-rendered CT image <b>(a)</b> and on curved multiplanar reformatted CT images of the left coronary artery <b>(b)</b> and right coronary artery <b>(c)</b>. (Images courtesy of Nobuo Iguchi, MD, PhD, Department of Cardiology, Sakakibara Heart Institute, Tokyo, Japan.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig4a.jpeg" height="824" width="664" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Stair-step artifacts. On curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b>, the stair-step artifacts are shown as coronary vessel discontinuity (arrows in a, c) on the images obtained without the intelligent boundary registration algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on the images obtained with the use of this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. In <b>c</b>, artifacts are shown on the coronary vessels crossed by the extended line of the shaft of each arrow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig4b.jpeg" height="824" width="662" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Stair-step artifacts. On curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b>, the stair-step artifacts are shown as coronary vessel discontinuity (arrows in a, c) on the images obtained without the intelligent boundary registration algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on the images obtained with the use of this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. In <b>c</b>, artifacts are shown on the coronary vessels crossed by the extended line of the shaft of each arrow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig4c.jpeg" height="575" width="784" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Stair-step artifacts. On curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b>, the stair-step artifacts are shown as coronary vessel discontinuity (arrows in a, c) on the images obtained without the intelligent boundary registration algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on the images obtained with the use of this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. In <b>c</b>, artifacts are shown on the coronary vessels crossed by the extended line of the shaft of each arrow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig4d.jpeg" height="575" width="691" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Stair-step artifacts. On curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b>, the stair-step artifacts are shown as coronary vessel discontinuity (arrows in a, c) on the images obtained without the intelligent boundary registration algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on the images obtained with the use of this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. In <b>c</b>, artifacts are shown on the coronary vessels crossed by the extended line of the shaft of each arrow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig5a.jpeg" height="803" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Compared with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical CT image obtained with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation <b>(a)</b>, a curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image <b>(b)</b> of the same patient acquired 1 year later with a step-and-shoot scan and the same scanning parameters shows similar image quality but with a reduction of the effective dose from 21.6 to 3.7 mSv (83%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig5b.jpeg" height="803" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Compared with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical CT image obtained with <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-controlled tube current modulation <b>(a)</b>, a curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image <b>(b)</b> of the same patient acquired 1 year later with a step-and-shoot scan and the same scanning parameters shows similar image quality but with a reduction of the effective dose from 21.6 to 3.7 mSv (83%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig6a.jpeg" height="615" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image obtained with a step-and-shoot scan <b>(a)</b> shows reduced helical-related blurring and permits better delineation of the stent struts and the in-stent lumen, compared with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT image of the same patient obtained with a helical scan <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig6b.jpeg" height="615" width="612" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image obtained with a step-and-shoot scan <b>(a)</b> shows reduced helical-related blurring and permits better delineation of the stent struts and the in-stent lumen, compared with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated coronary CT image of the same patient obtained with a helical scan <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig7a.jpeg" height="664" width="664" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Compared with a non–high-definition coronary CT image acquired 4 years earlier <b>(a)</b>, a curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image of the same patient obtained with the combination of high-definition CT and an adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction algorithm with the same scanning parameters <b>(b)</b> shows improved spatial resolution and intraluminal coronary vessel assessment without appreciably increased image noise in a patient with severe coronary calcification and coronary stents.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig7b.jpeg" height="664" width="660" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Compared with a non–high-definition coronary CT image acquired 4 years earlier <b>(a)</b>, a curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT image of the same patient obtained with the combination of high-definition CT and an adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction algorithm with the same scanning parameters <b>(b)</b> shows improved spatial resolution and intraluminal coronary vessel assessment without appreciably increased image noise in a patient with severe coronary calcification and coronary stents.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig8a.jpeg" height="665" width="665" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Compared with the non–high-definition coronary CT images <b>(a, c)</b>, the high-definition coronary CT images <b>(b, d)</b>, which were reconstructed with a more limited field of view, a harder-kernel “HD detail,” and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction at a 70% blending ratio with filtered backprojection, show improved depiction of in-stent restenosis for better diagnostic accuracy and show better delineation of the stent struts with higher spatial resolution and adequate image quality on curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> in a patient with a sirolimus-eluting stent (Cypher; Cordis, Miami Lakes, Fla) 3 mm in diameter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig8b.jpeg" height="665" width="661" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Compared with the non–high-definition coronary CT images <b>(a, c)</b>, the high-definition coronary CT images <b>(b, d)</b>, which were reconstructed with a more limited field of view, a harder-kernel “HD detail,” and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction at a 70% blending ratio with filtered backprojection, show improved depiction of in-stent restenosis for better diagnostic accuracy and show better delineation of the stent struts with higher spatial resolution and adequate image quality on curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> in a patient with a sirolimus-eluting stent (Cypher; Cordis, Miami Lakes, Fla) 3 mm in diameter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig8c.jpeg" height="477" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Compared with the non–high-definition coronary CT images <b>(a, c)</b>, the high-definition coronary CT images <b>(b, d)</b>, which were reconstructed with a more limited field of view, a harder-kernel “HD detail,” and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction at a 70% blending ratio with filtered backprojection, show improved depiction of in-stent restenosis for better diagnostic accuracy and show better delineation of the stent struts with higher spatial resolution and adequate image quality on curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> in a patient with a sirolimus-eluting stent (Cypher; Cordis, Miami Lakes, Fla) 3 mm in diameter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig8d.jpeg" height="477" width="624" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span> Compared with the non–high-definition coronary CT images <b>(a, c)</b>, the high-definition coronary CT images <b>(b, d)</b>, which were reconstructed with a more limited field of view, a harder-kernel “HD detail,” and adaptive statistical iterative reconstruction at a 70% blending ratio with filtered backprojection, show improved depiction of in-stent restenosis for better diagnostic accuracy and show better delineation of the stent struts with higher spatial resolution and adequate image quality on curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> in a patient with a sirolimus-eluting stent (Cypher; Cordis, Miami Lakes, Fla) 3 mm in diameter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig9a.jpeg" height="575" width="949" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with a low and regular heart rate of 49–51 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts and degraded delineation of chronic total occlusion in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a step-and-shoot scan and reconstructed at 80% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig9b.jpeg" height="575" width="826" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with a low and regular heart rate of 49–51 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts and degraded delineation of chronic total occlusion in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a step-and-shoot scan and reconstructed at 80% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig9c.jpeg" height="772" width="446" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with a low and regular heart rate of 49–51 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts and degraded delineation of chronic total occlusion in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a step-and-shoot scan and reconstructed at 80% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig9d.jpeg" height="772" width="429" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with a low and regular heart rate of 49–51 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts and degraded delineation of chronic total occlusion in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and cross-sectional coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a step-and-shoot scan and reconstructed at 80% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig10a.jpeg" height="880" width="722" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with relatively high heart rate of 74–77 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan and reconstructed at 40% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig10b.jpeg" height="880" width="753" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with relatively high heart rate of 74–77 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan and reconstructed at 40% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig10c.jpeg" height="768" width="804" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with relatively high heart rate of 74–77 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan and reconstructed at 40% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig10d.jpeg" height="768" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Motion artifacts. In a patient with relatively high heart rate of 74–77 beats per minute during scanning, severe motion artifacts in the right coronary artery are shown on images obtained without the motion correction algorithm <b>(a, c)</b> but are reduced on images obtained with this algorithm <b>(b, d)</b>. Curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and volume-rendered coronary CT images <b>(c, d)</b> were acquired with a retrospective <abbr title="electrocardiography">ECG</abbr>-gated helical scan and reconstructed at 40% of the R-R interval.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig11a.jpeg" height="904" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> In a patient with small collateral vessels of the conus branch between the right coronary artery and the left anterior descending coronary artery, a monochromatic image obtained at 40 keV displayed as a volume-rendered coronary CT image <b>(a)</b> shows improved delineation of the collateral vessels compared with volume-rendered coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching at higher energy levels of 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 100 keV <b>(c)</b>. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig11b.jpeg" height="948" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> In a patient with small collateral vessels of the conus branch between the right coronary artery and the left anterior descending coronary artery, a monochromatic image obtained at 40 keV displayed as a volume-rendered coronary CT image <b>(a)</b> shows improved delineation of the collateral vessels compared with volume-rendered coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching at higher energy levels of 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 100 keV <b>(c)</b>. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig11c.jpeg" height="948" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> In a patient with small collateral vessels of the conus branch between the right coronary artery and the left anterior descending coronary artery, a monochromatic image obtained at 40 keV displayed as a volume-rendered coronary CT image <b>(a)</b> shows improved delineation of the collateral vessels compared with volume-rendered coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching at higher energy levels of 70 keV <b>(b)</b> and 100 keV <b>(c)</b>. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig12a.jpeg" height="1030" width="515" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Compared with monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a, b)</b>, material density images obtained with iodine and hydroxyapatite selected as the basis pair <b>(c, d)</b> show removed or decreased depiction of calcified coronary plaques, allowing a detailed evaluation of the lumen of the left coronary artery <b>(a, c)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(b, d)</b> on the curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig12b.jpeg" height="1030" width="395" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Compared with monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a, b)</b>, material density images obtained with iodine and hydroxyapatite selected as the basis pair <b>(c, d)</b> show removed or decreased depiction of calcified coronary plaques, allowing a detailed evaluation of the lumen of the left coronary artery <b>(a, c)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(b, d)</b> on the curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig12c.jpeg" height="1030" width="521" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Compared with monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a, b)</b>, material density images obtained with iodine and hydroxyapatite selected as the basis pair <b>(c, d)</b> show removed or decreased depiction of calcified coronary plaques, allowing a detailed evaluation of the lumen of the left coronary artery <b>(a, c)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(b, d)</b> on the curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig12d.jpeg" height="1030" width="395" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Compared with monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a, b)</b>, material density images obtained with iodine and hydroxyapatite selected as the basis pair <b>(c, d)</b> show removed or decreased depiction of calcified coronary plaques, allowing a detailed evaluation of the lumen of the left coronary artery <b>(a, c)</b> and the right coronary artery <b>(b, d)</b> on the curved multiplanar reformatted coronary CT images. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig13a.jpeg" height="640" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Cross-sectional coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching. Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which it is difficult to determine whether the noncalcified coronary plaque is either lipid-rich or fibrous plaque, fusion with a color-coded material density image obtained with fat and water selected as the basis pair <b>(b)</b> can easily depict subtle lipid in the plaque as a colored area similar to pericardial fat, a finding that is suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. <b>(c)</b> Spectral Hounsfield unit curve for the colored area of plaque in <b>b</b> shows a pattern of decreased attenuation with lower energy levels (kiloelectron volts), a finding that is also suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig13b.jpeg" height="640" width="721" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Cross-sectional coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching. Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which it is difficult to determine whether the noncalcified coronary plaque is either lipid-rich or fibrous plaque, fusion with a color-coded material density image obtained with fat and water selected as the basis pair <b>(b)</b> can easily depict subtle lipid in the plaque as a colored area similar to pericardial fat, a finding that is suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. <b>(c)</b> Spectral Hounsfield unit curve for the colored area of plaque in <b>b</b> shows a pattern of decreased attenuation with lower energy levels (kiloelectron volts), a finding that is also suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig13c.jpeg" height="758" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Cross-sectional coronary CT images obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching. Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which it is difficult to determine whether the noncalcified coronary plaque is either lipid-rich or fibrous plaque, fusion with a color-coded material density image obtained with fat and water selected as the basis pair <b>(b)</b> can easily depict subtle lipid in the plaque as a colored area similar to pericardial fat, a finding that is suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. <b>(c)</b> Spectral Hounsfield unit curve for the colored area of plaque in <b>b</b> shows a pattern of decreased attenuation with lower energy levels (kiloelectron volts), a finding that is also suggestive of lipid-rich plaque. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig14a.jpeg" height="781" width="699" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which regions of interest are placed within the iodine-filled vessel lumen (red oval), the fibrous plaque (pink oval), the lipid-rich plaque (light blue circle), and the pericardial fat (dark blue oval) on a cross-sectional coronary CT image obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching, the spectral Hounsfield unit curve <b>(b)</b> and the histogram of effective Z <b>(c)</b> can easily be used to identify lipid-rich plaque. In <b>b</b>, which represents the energy level (in kiloelectron volts) on the x-axis and the attenuation value (in Hounsfield units) on the y-axis, the curve pattern of lipid-rich plaque (light blue curve) shows decreased attenuation with lower energy levels, similar to the pattern of pericardial fat (dark blue curve) and different from the pattern for the vessel lumen (red curve) and fibrous plaque (pink curve). In <b>c</b>, which represents effective Z on the x-axis (the vertical blue line represents the theoretical effective Z for fat) and the percentage of pixels on the y-axis, the lipid-rich plaque (light blue) shows a peak and distribution similar to those of pericardial fat (dark blue) and different from those of the vessel lumen (red) and fibrous plaque (pink). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig14b.jpeg" height="1037" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which regions of interest are placed within the iodine-filled vessel lumen (red oval), the fibrous plaque (pink oval), the lipid-rich plaque (light blue circle), and the pericardial fat (dark blue oval) on a cross-sectional coronary CT image obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching, the spectral Hounsfield unit curve <b>(b)</b> and the histogram of effective Z <b>(c)</b> can easily be used to identify lipid-rich plaque. In <b>b</b>, which represents the energy level (in kiloelectron volts) on the x-axis and the attenuation value (in Hounsfield units) on the y-axis, the curve pattern of lipid-rich plaque (light blue curve) shows decreased attenuation with lower energy levels, similar to the pattern of pericardial fat (dark blue curve) and different from the pattern for the vessel lumen (red curve) and fibrous plaque (pink curve). In <b>c</b>, which represents effective Z on the x-axis (the vertical blue line represents the theoretical effective Z for fat) and the percentage of pixels on the y-axis, the lipid-rich plaque (light blue) shows a peak and distribution similar to those of pericardial fat (dark blue) and different from those of the vessel lumen (red) and fibrous plaque (pink). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig14c.jpeg" height="1037" width="939" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Compared with a monochromatic image obtained at 65 keV <b>(a)</b>, on which regions of interest are placed within the iodine-filled vessel lumen (red oval), the fibrous plaque (pink oval), the lipid-rich plaque (light blue circle), and the pericardial fat (dark blue oval) on a cross-sectional coronary CT image obtained with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching, the spectral Hounsfield unit curve <b>(b)</b> and the histogram of effective Z <b>(c)</b> can easily be used to identify lipid-rich plaque. In <b>b</b>, which represents the energy level (in kiloelectron volts) on the x-axis and the attenuation value (in Hounsfield units) on the y-axis, the curve pattern of lipid-rich plaque (light blue curve) shows decreased attenuation with lower energy levels, similar to the pattern of pericardial fat (dark blue curve) and different from the pattern for the vessel lumen (red curve) and fibrous plaque (pink curve). In <b>c</b>, which represents effective Z on the x-axis (the vertical blue line represents the theoretical effective Z for fat) and the percentage of pixels on the y-axis, the lipid-rich plaque (light blue) shows a peak and distribution similar to those of pericardial fat (dark blue) and different from those of the vessel lumen (red) and fibrous plaque (pink). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig15a.jpeg" height="903" width="792" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> <b>(a, c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching show regions of interest placed for coronary plaque component analysis in the left anterior descending coronary artery (segment 6) (red circle in <b>a</b>) and in the right coronary artery (segment 1) (red circle in <b>c</b>). <b>(b, d)</b> Histograms of effective Z (thick vertical yellow bars) in each pixel within the two regions of interest show that the major component of the calcification in <b>a</b> is hydroxyapatite <i>(HAP)</i> or tricalcium phosphate <i>(TCP)</i> <b>(b)</b> and that the major component of the calcification in <b>c</b> is calcium oxalate monohydrate <i>(Caoxymono)</i> <b>(d)</b>. From left to right, the thin vertical colored lines in the histograms represent the theoretical effective Z for octacalcium phosphate <i>(OCP)</i> (red), dicalcium phosphate dehydrate <i>(DCPD)</i> (green), calcium oxalate monohydrate (blue), hydroxyapatite (yellow), and tricalcium phosphate (blue).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig15b.jpeg" height="903" width="982" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> <b>(a, c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching show regions of interest placed for coronary plaque component analysis in the left anterior descending coronary artery (segment 6) (red circle in <b>a</b>) and in the right coronary artery (segment 1) (red circle in <b>c</b>). <b>(b, d)</b> Histograms of effective Z (thick vertical yellow bars) in each pixel within the two regions of interest show that the major component of the calcification in <b>a</b> is hydroxyapatite <i>(HAP)</i> or tricalcium phosphate <i>(TCP)</i> <b>(b)</b> and that the major component of the calcification in <b>c</b> is calcium oxalate monohydrate <i>(Caoxymono)</i> <b>(d)</b>. From left to right, the thin vertical colored lines in the histograms represent the theoretical effective Z for octacalcium phosphate <i>(OCP)</i> (red), dicalcium phosphate dehydrate <i>(DCPD)</i> (green), calcium oxalate monohydrate (blue), hydroxyapatite (yellow), and tricalcium phosphate (blue).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig15c.jpeg" height="903" width="790" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> <b>(a, c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching show regions of interest placed for coronary plaque component analysis in the left anterior descending coronary artery (segment 6) (red circle in <b>a</b>) and in the right coronary artery (segment 1) (red circle in <b>c</b>). <b>(b, d)</b> Histograms of effective Z (thick vertical yellow bars) in each pixel within the two regions of interest show that the major component of the calcification in <b>a</b> is hydroxyapatite <i>(HAP)</i> or tricalcium phosphate <i>(TCP)</i> <b>(b)</b> and that the major component of the calcification in <b>c</b> is calcium oxalate monohydrate <i>(Caoxymono)</i> <b>(d)</b>. From left to right, the thin vertical colored lines in the histograms represent the theoretical effective Z for octacalcium phosphate <i>(OCP)</i> (red), dicalcium phosphate dehydrate <i>(DCPD)</i> (green), calcium oxalate monohydrate (blue), hydroxyapatite (yellow), and tricalcium phosphate (blue).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig15d.jpeg" height="903" width="980" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span> <b>(a, c)</b> Curved multiplanar reformatted monochromatic images obtained at 65 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching show regions of interest placed for coronary plaque component analysis in the left anterior descending coronary artery (segment 6) (red circle in <b>a</b>) and in the right coronary artery (segment 1) (red circle in <b>c</b>). <b>(b, d)</b> Histograms of effective Z (thick vertical yellow bars) in each pixel within the two regions of interest show that the major component of the calcification in <b>a</b> is hydroxyapatite <i>(HAP)</i> or tricalcium phosphate <i>(TCP)</i> <b>(b)</b> and that the major component of the calcification in <b>c</b> is calcium oxalate monohydrate <i>(Caoxymono)</i> <b>(d)</b>. From left to right, the thin vertical colored lines in the histograms represent the theoretical effective Z for octacalcium phosphate <i>(OCP)</i> (red), dicalcium phosphate dehydrate <i>(DCPD)</i> (green), calcium oxalate monohydrate (blue), hydroxyapatite (yellow), and tricalcium phosphate (blue).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig16a.jpeg" height="738" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <b>(a–d)</b> In comparison with a monochromatic short-axis myocardial perfusion image obtained at 70 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a)</b>, material density image <b>(b)</b> and fusion of a color-coded material density image <b>(c)</b> obtained with iodine and water selected as the basis pair more clearly delineate perfusion defects in the anterior wall of the left ventricle, allowing quantitation of myocardial perfusion as iodine density in regions of interest placed in the anterior wall (yellow circle in <b>d</b>), lateral wall (green circle in <b>d</b>), and inferior wall (blue circle in <b>d</b>). Iodine density of 0.01, 1.62, and 1.56 mg/mL was measured in these three regions. <b>(e)</b> Three-dimensionally matched fusion of volume-rendered color-coded material density and coronary CT images generated from the same CT dataset is useful to easily and precisely identify the diagonal branch as a culprit vessel. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig16b.jpeg" height="738" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <b>(a–d)</b> In comparison with a monochromatic short-axis myocardial perfusion image obtained at 70 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a)</b>, material density image <b>(b)</b> and fusion of a color-coded material density image <b>(c)</b> obtained with iodine and water selected as the basis pair more clearly delineate perfusion defects in the anterior wall of the left ventricle, allowing quantitation of myocardial perfusion as iodine density in regions of interest placed in the anterior wall (yellow circle in <b>d</b>), lateral wall (green circle in <b>d</b>), and inferior wall (blue circle in <b>d</b>). Iodine density of 0.01, 1.62, and 1.56 mg/mL was measured in these three regions. <b>(e)</b> Three-dimensionally matched fusion of volume-rendered color-coded material density and coronary CT images generated from the same CT dataset is useful to easily and precisely identify the diagonal branch as a culprit vessel. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig16c.jpeg" height="745" width="746" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> <b>(a–d)</b> In comparison with a monochromatic short-axis myocardial perfusion image obtained at 70 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a)</b>, material density image <b>(b)</b> and fusion of a color-coded material density image <b>(c)</b> obtained with iodine and water selected as the basis pair more clearly delineate perfusion defects in the anterior wall of the left ventricle, allowing quantitation of myocardial perfusion as iodine density in regions of interest placed in the anterior wall (yellow circle in <b>d</b>), lateral wall (green circle in <b>d</b>), and inferior wall (blue circle in <b>d</b>). Iodine density of 0.01, 1.62, and 1.56 mg/mL was measured in these three regions. <b>(e)</b> Three-dimensionally matched fusion of volume-rendered color-coded material density and coronary CT images generated from the same CT dataset is useful to easily and precisely identify the diagonal branch as a culprit vessel. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig16d.jpeg" height="745" width="729" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> <b>(a–d)</b> In comparison with a monochromatic short-axis myocardial perfusion image obtained at 70 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a)</b>, material density image <b>(b)</b> and fusion of a color-coded material density image <b>(c)</b> obtained with iodine and water selected as the basis pair more clearly delineate perfusion defects in the anterior wall of the left ventricle, allowing quantitation of myocardial perfusion as iodine density in regions of interest placed in the anterior wall (yellow circle in <b>d</b>), lateral wall (green circle in <b>d</b>), and inferior wall (blue circle in <b>d</b>). Iodine density of 0.01, 1.62, and 1.56 mg/mL was measured in these three regions. <b>(e)</b> Three-dimensionally matched fusion of volume-rendered color-coded material density and coronary CT images generated from the same CT dataset is useful to easily and precisely identify the diagonal branch as a culprit vessel. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig16e.jpeg" height="944" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16e</span> <b>(a–d)</b> In comparison with a monochromatic short-axis myocardial perfusion image obtained at 70 keV with single-source dual-energy CT with fast tube voltage switching <b>(a)</b>, material density image <b>(b)</b> and fusion of a color-coded material density image <b>(c)</b> obtained with iodine and water selected as the basis pair more clearly delineate perfusion defects in the anterior wall of the left ventricle, allowing quantitation of myocardial perfusion as iodine density in regions of interest placed in the anterior wall (yellow circle in <b>d</b>), lateral wall (green circle in <b>d</b>), and inferior wall (blue circle in <b>d</b>). Iodine density of 0.01, 1.62, and 1.56 mg/mL was measured in these three regions. <b>(e)</b> Three-dimensionally matched fusion of volume-rendered color-coded material density and coronary CT images generated from the same CT dataset is useful to easily and precisely identify the diagonal branch as a culprit vessel. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r45" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r45">45</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig16e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140181/asset/images/large/rg.2015140181.fig17.jpeg" height="857" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Example of an <abbr title="fractional flow reserve derived from CT">FFR</abbr> image has color contours that provide data on the distribution of <abbr title="fractional flow reserve derived from CT">FFR</abbr> throughout the coronary tree. Numerical <abbr title="fractional flow reserve derived from CT">FFR</abbr> values can be obtained at any location. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r50" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r50">50</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140181&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Budoff MJ, Achenbach S, Blumenthal RS, et al. Assessment of coronary artery disease by cardiac computed tomography: a scientific statement from the American Heart Association Committee on Cardiovascular Imaging and Intervention, Council on Cardiovascular Radiology and Intervention, and Committee on Cardiac Imaging, Council on Clinical Cardiology. <em>Circulation</em> 2006;114(16):1761–1791.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.106.178458">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17015792/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Assessment+of+coronary+artery+disease+by+cardiac+computed+tomography%3A+a+scientific+statement+from+the+American+Heart+Association+Committee+on+Cardiovascular+Imaging+and+Intervention%2C+Council+on+Cardiovascular+Radiology+and+Intervention%2C+and+Committee+on+Cardiac+Imaging%2C+Council+on+Clinical+Cardiology&amp;author=MJ+Budoff&amp;author=S+Achenbach&amp;author=RS+Blumenthal&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Circulation&amp;pages=1761-1791&amp;doi=10.1161%2FCIRCULATIONAHA.106.178458&amp;pmid=17015792">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Miller JM, Rochitte CE, Dewey M, et al. Diagnostic performance of coronary angiography by 64-row CT. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2008;359(22):2324–2336.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa0806576">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19038879/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Diagnostic+performance+of+coronary+angiography+by+64-row+CT&amp;author=JM+Miller&amp;author=CE+Rochitte&amp;author=M+Dewey&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=N+Engl+J+Med&amp;pages=2324-2336&amp;doi=10.1056%2FNEJMoa0806576&amp;pmid=19038879">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citatio